title: Bengals rally to run record to 5 - 0
text:
Bengals rally to run record to 5 - 0 
By WISE Web Sports Cincinnati Bengals tight end Tyler Eifert. October 11, 2015 Updated Oct 11, 2015 at 5:45 PM EDT 
(Cincinnati, Ohio) -- Quarterback Andy Dalton led Cincinnati back from a 17 - point fourth - quarter deficit and the Bengals rallied to beat Seattle 27 - 24 in overtime. Dalton threw two touchdown passes to Bishop Dwenger and Notre Dame graduate Tyler Eifert, plus, he ran for another score. Kicker Mike Nugent caromed the game - winning field goal off of the left goal post and through for the win. Cincinnati is now in command of the AFC's North Division with a 5 - 0 record.
